entry.title: [FSA] Update `queryPermission()` to include persistent permission state.
entry.content:
Previously, even if a handle has persistent permission,

`queryPermission()` could return `PermissionStatus::ASK`; only when

`requestPermission()` is called, the persistent permission status would

be retrieved for auto-granting. However, this could be a confusing

behavior to API users, as the persistence of permission is

implementation detail.



`FileSystemAccessPermissionGrant.GetStatus()` is now updated to read

from persisted grant objects and to return the combined state between

active and persisted grants. This method is used not only for

`queryPermission()` API, but also in various places internally such as

returning child handles from a parent directory handle.



Instead of introducing a new `GetPersistedStatus()`, the existing

`GetStatus()` is updated to account for persistent permission.

Additionally, a new private method `GetActivePermissionStatus()` is

introduced to replace the former usage of `GetStatus()` within

`ChromeFileSystemAccessPermissionContext`.

entry.title: [views] Fix Widget parenting in ConstrainedWindowViewsTest
entry.content:
This CL updates ConstrainedWindowViewsTest to ensure the dialog

and the dialog host have independent NativeViews.



The current test implementation is not strictly correct as the

both the dialog and the host share the same NativeView. This

results in updates to the dialog's bounds also applying to the

dialog's host. This is not expected application behavior and

can result in unexpected results if host bounds are ever asserted.



This CL also adjust the preferred size of the contents to 400x400.

The default screen size is 800x600 and the current 500x500 size

can start to push the dialog outside the bounds of the display

given current tested size changes and taking into account UI

elements such as frame headers.

entry.title: Update SpacingRecyclerViewItemDecoration to be configurable.
entry.content:
In order to address issues resulting from crrev/c/4990273/, we will

have to dynamically re-calculate lead-in and element spacing each time

RecyclerView measured dimension change.



There are two ways to go about it:

1. remove old and create a new spacing element - may not be needed if

dimensions don't change; also, object allocation during measure is

discouraged

2. update existing decorations by applying new sizes and optionally

invalidating item decorations, if the new spacing differs.



This change prepares SpacingRecyclerViewItemDecoration to work with

the 2nd variant.

entry.title: Android: Skip releases without valid artifacts
entry.content:
fetch_github_release.py supports two operations:

- latest: gets the latest release version

- get_urls: get the urls for a specific version (usually latest)



Previously only get_urls actually checked whether a specific release has

an artifact that we want and failed if it did not. Thus if the latest

release did not have the artifact we want, then latest would happily

return that release version despite knowing get_urls would fail.



This CL switches us to checking releases one by one starting with the

latest one, and returning the first release that contains the artifacts

that we want. This ensures that get_urls would not fail if latest

succeeds.



Also rename 3pp to 3pp_common so that the 3pp try bot does not get

confused by an invalid //build/3pp directory.

entry.title: Create PrefetchServingPageMetricsContainer in NavigationRequest
entry.content:
This CL



- Removes dependencies from `PrefetchServingPageMetrics`

to `PrefetchDocumentManager::DidStartNavigation()`.

- Creates and records the metrics for

prefetch-in-new-tab cases (crbug.com/1432886).



Before this CL, `PrefetchServingPageMetricsContainer`

is created and set to `PrefetchContainer` in

`PrefetchDocumentManager::DidStartNavigation()`.



After this CL, `PrefetchServingPageMetricsContainer`

is created in `NavigationRequest`,

plumbed to `NavigationRequestInfo`

-> `PrefetchURLLoaderInterceptor`

-> `PrefetchService::GetPrefetchToServe()`,

and set to `PrefetchContainer` there.



This CL creates `PrefetchServingPageMetricsContainer`

even if `PrefetchDocumentManager::DidStartNavigation()`

isn't called, but still creates the metrics container

only when the initiator Document has its

`PrefetchDocumentManager`,

in order to avoid recording the metrics

for much broader range of Documents where

speculation rules prefetch is not used at all.



`SetMetricsForPossibleNoVarySearchHintMatches()`

is no longer needed, as all potential matches

including No-Vary-Search hint candidates are iterated

in `PrefetchService::FindPrefetchContainerToServe()`.

entry.title: Fix tests for changing browser context type
entry.content:
The shared browser main thread context is going to switch from GLES2

decoder backed context to a raster decoder backed context. There are two

test that fail when this switch happens that need to be fixed.



CaptureModeCameraFramesTest uses PaintCanvasVideoRenderer to copy a

video frame to a bitmap. PaintCanvasVideoRenderer needs a context that

supports GPU rasterization and the browser main thread context won't

after the switch. Have the test create it's own context.



BufferTest.IsLost was triggering context loss on the main thread

context. With GLES2 decoder this is limited to just the GL context but

with raster decoder it causes a context loss on SharedContextState,

which fails the test and starts tearing down parts of the GPU thread.

The test is about handling context loss client side, so have the main

thread context send out an OnContextLost() message to observers instead

of triggering a real context loss.

entry.title: [User Education] Some restructuring in components/user_education
entry.content:
Moves and renames some data structures and enumerations for clarity and for use in follow-up CLs (mostly from feature_promo_storage_service.h to feature_promo_data.h)



Removes two files that had been accidentally checked in but were not ready to be used.



The major renames here are (1) FeaturePromoCloseReason > EndFeaturePromoReason and (2) CloseReason > FeaturePromoClosedReason.



The reason for these are that FeaturePromoCloseReason and CloseReason are too similar and it's confusing which one to use in any particular situation (both are part of the public API). With the latter being moved up into feature_promo_data.h, it makes it harder to give it a name that is not ambiguous with the former. The specific names chosen are:



EndFeaturePromoReason (1) is used when client code that starts a promo wants to end it, for example, in response to the user using the feature the promo is attached to. So it's explicitly an "I'm ending this promo" reason.



FeaturePromoClosedReason (2) is used to signal why an IPH ended, while/after it is ending. This could be programmatically as above or for a number of other reasons, including being dismissed by the user, being pre-empted, having its UI change underneath it, etc.

entry.title: infra: Make new win builders default to builderless

Making windows bots not default to builderless likely leads to folks

spinning up builders that ought to be builderless but aren't, eg:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Win10%20Tests%20x64%20%28dbg%29

machine utilization and easier resource management. So this changes the

default so that, when not specified, win builders will be builderless

by default.



We keep mac out of the default since we only run win and linux on GCE,

and the ease of GCE deployments is partly what enables builderless.

entry.title: Fix gpu_unittests running under UBSan
entry.content:
This is mostly a mess of alignment/type-punning issues. First, random

pointers cannot be cast to uint32_t* because they won't be aligned.

Instead, type-punning loads and stores can be done through memcpy.



Second, packed structs are very irritating when combined with EXPECT_EQ.

It isn't safe to take a pointer to a field in a packed struct, but

EXPECT_EQ internally does so. Copy fields to temporary values before

passing to EXPECT_EQ.

entry.title: [Hub] Add shrink and expand animation support
entry.content:
Create shrink and expand animations for Hub. These are borrowed from

TabSwitcherLayout, but the implementation is much more ergonomic.



The ShrinkExpandHubLayoutAnimatorProvider owns and attaches a

ShrinkExpandImageView to the HubContainerView. This view is initially

invisible.



If a bitmap is needed a bitmap callback is created that will set the

image on the ShrinkExpandImageView when ready. This callback uses weak

references to prevent retaining refs to the view or the animator

provider in the event it gets held in native for a prolonged duration

and the fallback animator runs.



The animator provider waits for the bitmap and some asynchronously

supplied data regarding initial and final rects for the animation to

be supplied. The external caller can also cancel the animation to use

the fallback through this supplier. This is a holdover from the

TabSwitcherLayout which must skip an animation is the

TabListRecyclerView has too much work to do and can hopefully be

removed in the future.



Once the animator provider has all the data it will supply the

Animator. Unless a fallback animation is requested beforehand in which

case a fade animation will be provided for the shrink/expand case or

the animation will proceed in the case of the new tab animation.

entry.title: [X11] Move utils into x11::Connection
entry.content:
The motivation for this CL is to eventually move ui/base/x/x11_util

into x11::Connection. x11_util has a lot of utilities that perform

frequent blocking calls (eg WmSupportsHint() is called on every mouse

event in the non-client area). A simple x11::PropertyCache is

sufficient to avoid blocking, but ownership of the cache becomes

an issue since x11_util only contains free functions. In the GPU

process, x11_util may be used from multiple threads with their own

connections, so we really need a per-connection cache. The current

solution avoids the issue because x11::Connection::Get() gets the

TLS Connection instance to do each blocking call.

entry.title: Leave inflow position alone when resuming a parallel flow.
entry.content:
ComputeInflowPosition() would reset the margin strut, and thus we'd lose

the MarginStrut::discard_margins flag. This flag is set to truncate

margins at unforced breaks, and needs to remain true as long as we

haven't added any in-flow content to the next fragmentainer. The bug was

that the block-start margin of some child would be re-applied after an

unforced break, because this flag was reset prematurely.



The crash in crbug.com/1494668 was caused by this correctness issue. It

caused inline elements to become non-contiguous unexpectedly. E.g.

there's a fragment item for a SPAN in the first and the third columns,

but not in the second, due to a large margin, that should have been

ignored.
